[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     86[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Problem:** The recipe correctly elevates concept-drift-as-silent-and-constant, per-SKU forecast-error-vs-actuals tracking, two-consecutive-cycle alerting on high-value SKUs, and retraining cadence (monthly is reasonable for most segments) plus retraining-on-demand-when-drift-is-detected. Despite this elevation, the architecture pattern, the Mermaid diagram, and the pseudocode treat monitoring as a CloudWatch-alarm-on-pipeline-errors primitive rather than as a per-SKU, per-segment, per-cohort forecast-quality SLO with launch-gate threshold values. The Step 3 quality gate ("REJECT this model; alert the ML engineer / IF error > current_production_model[segment_label].error * 1.20") is correct at the segment level but does not cover the per-SKU forecast-vs-actual feedback loop that runs continuously after deployment.
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     87[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Fix:** Add a "Per-Segment and Per-SKU Forecast Monitoring with Launch-Gate Discipline" subsection to the General Architecture Pattern. Specify (1) a rolling per-SKU forecast-error-vs-actual feedback table (DynamoDB or Timestream) populated by a daily Lambda that joins yesterday's actual consumption against the forecast issued for that day; (2) per-segment SLO thresholds (smooth: 30-day MAPE < target, intermittent: 30-day MASE < 1.0, procedure-driven: forecast-vs-actual ratio within target band, lumpy: monitored at the rolled-up category level); (3) two-axis cohort stratification (high-value SKUs measured by annual spend / clinical-criticality-tier; volume-tier; segment); (4) launch-gate threshold values for new model versions (block deployment if validation MAPE / MASE exceeds threshold or regresses materially against the production model); (5) retraining cadence per segment (monthly default; on-demand when drift detected; cold-start retraining on a separate cadence). Match the chapter-pattern from 11.6's A1 / 11.7's A1 finding.
