[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     94[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Quote:** "Procedure-driven SKUs go through a two-stage model: forecast cases, multiply by per-case usage."
[0m[49m[38;5;10m+     95[0m:[38;5;10m[49m - **Problem:** The procedure-driven branch of the segmentation depends on a case-volume forecast as input. The pseudocode references `forecasted_cases(facility, date)` without specifying where that lookup goes (the Recipe 12.1 forecast output, the OR scheduling system's confirmed-case projection, the surgical-scheduling integration layer, or some hybrid). Operationally, the answer matters: the OR schedule three weeks out is a much stronger signal than the historical-pattern forecast, and a confirmed case three days out is essentially deterministic. The architecture should specify (1) which signal sources feed the lookup; (2) how they are reconciled (precedence: confirmed-case over OR-schedule over Recipe-12.1-forecast over fallback historical mean); (3) the freshness contract (case forecasts refreshed at least daily for procedure-driven SKUs, not on the weekly cadence of the rest of the pipeline); (4) the failure mode if the lookup is unavailable (fall back to historical mean per case, alert the ML engineer, do not silently emit zeros).
